<section xml:id="sec-Answers53">
  <title>Answers</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Toprepareforclass53">
    <title>To prepare for class</title>
    
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        The blue and green regions have exactly the same area.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\sin(x^{3}) + C</m>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Yes, it matches.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>

    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Afterclass53">
      <title>After class</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle \int x^{3} \sqrt{x^{4}+5}\ dx</m> by letting <m>u(x) = x^{4} + 5 = \frac{1}{6}(x^{4}+5)^{3/2}+ C</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>u(x) = x+2</m>.
        Then <m>x = u-2</m>.
        This allows one to write the integral in terms of <m>u</m> rather easily.
        Thus, <m>\displaystyle \int x\sqrt{x+2}\ dx = \frac{2}{5}(x+2)^{5/2}- \frac{4}{3}(x+2)^{3/2}+C</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Use the substitution <m>u=\cos x</m>.
        Then <m>\displaystyle \int \tan(x) \ dx = \int \frac{\sin x}{\cos x}\ dx = -\int \frac{1}{u}\ du = -\ln |\cos x| + C</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle \int \sec(x) \ dx = \ln | \sec x + \tan x | + C</m>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</subsection>
